thread.title: Wet weekend ahead, with high winds and heavy rain expected
thread.title_full: Wet weekend ahead, with high winds and heavy rain expected | The Seattle Times

author: Christine Clarridge
title: Wet weekend ahead, with high winds and heavy rain expected
text:
It’s looking like a wet, windy weekend for residents of Seattle and the rest of the Puget Sound area as a rare summer storm moves in.
The National Weather Service forecasts a Pacific storm on Saturday that’s expected to bring strong winds and heavy rain.
The system could bring winds of up to 20 to 35 mph with gusts of 45 to 50 mph on parts of the coast, the northwest interior and the Interstate 5 corridor, the weather service predicts.
Winds this strong usually occur in fall and winter, according to the weather service. Those gusts could cause some tree limbs to snap, especially on deciduous trees, and lead to power outages.
Most Read Stories Mariners fire general manager Jack Zduriencik Now comes the hard part for the Mariners: Hiring Jack Zduriencik’s replacement Mariners demote struggling catcher Mike Zunino Why Russell Wilson needs to water down his Recovery claims Animated map: How the wildfires in North Central Washington have grown over time The city is predicted to get anywhere from ¼ inch to 1 inch of rain over the weekend, and some areas along the coast could get as much as 3 inches during the 24-hour period ending Sunday afternoon.
The winds may be strong enough to interfere with outdoor events, especially those in tents and canopies, according to the warning.
In Western Washington, “This amount of rain will likely end or help reduce the size of any ongoing wildfires,” a weather service special advisory said.
Wind advisories were issued for some Western Washington and Seattle areas Friday afternoon.
The warning for the Seattle area, which is in effect from around 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. Saturday, forecasts winds of 15 to 30 mph, with gusts up to 45 mph.
In Eastern Washington, the weather service reports some concerns that the high winds could hurt efforts to battle the Okanogan complex fire — the largest in state history.
Fire officials, however, said they do not expect a repeat of the flare-ups that occurred last week when winds surged.
In the Puget Sound region, temperatures are predicted to be in the mid- to upper-60s across the lowlands.
For newcomers to the area who have not experienced the area’s famously wet weather, meteorologist Johnny Burg says, “Welcome to Seattle.”
Seattle Times staff reporters Hal Bernton and Jessica Lee contributed to this report. Christine Clarridge: 206-464-8983 or cclarridge@seattletimes.com .
